# Repository Scope Enforcement

## Rules

### ✅ Accept Only Backend Content

- **Backend API Development**: REST, GraphQL, gRPC, WebSocket servers
- **Database Layer**: Schema design, migrations, queries, optimization, ORM/query builders
- **Server Architecture**: Microservices, monoliths, service design, patterns
- **Authentication & Authorization**: JWT, OAuth, session management, RBAC, security policies
- **Performance & Monitoring**: Profiling, optimization, logging, tracing, metrics
- **DevOps & Infrastructure**: Docker, CI/CD, deployment, orchestration, infrastructure-as-code
- **Backend Testing**: Unit tests, integration tests, API tests, e2e backend tests
- **Backend Code Quality**: Refactoring, linting, security audits (server-side only)

### ❌ Reject Frontend Content

- **Frontend Frameworks**: React, Vue, Angular, Svelte, etc.
- **UI/UX**: Component design, styling, CSS, HTML templates, accessibility (UI)
- **Client-Side Logic**: Browser APIs, client state management, frontend routing
- **Fullstack Features**: Features that mix client and server concerns
- **Build Tools**: Webpack, Vite, Rollup (unless for backend bundling)

## Enforcement

When detecting out-of-scope content: Flag violation, explain why (reference `docs/REPOSITORY-GOALS.md`), suggest alternative ("backend-only" or "separate backend concerns"), recommend deletion if existing content violates scope.

**Reference**: `docs/REPOSITORY-GOALS.md` - Backend API, databases, server architecture, auth, performance, DevOps, testing (in scope); Frontend, fullstack, UI/UX, client-side (out of scope)
